Show HN: Click the Number Reaction Game
text:
Hello HN, yesterday, I stumbled over an old project of mine called Click The Number. It's a game I built six years ago to compare my speed and dexterity with that of my friends. You have to click the numbers in ascending order – as quickly as possible!

After the discovery, I couldn't resist and continued working on this project for a bit. I made the colors a bit nicer, update some of the code, and added a high score to make the game slightly more addictive. I now have more ideas than time to build them.

A friend of mine gave this game to their kids (who love it!) and recommended I should build an actual mobile game out of this. I replied that it is really hard to get a game like that off the ground, especially when there is no real "progress" you can make. What do you think about pursuing this? Are there variations of this theme that could make it work?

If you're interested, share your record on the leaderboard in the project's Readme [1]. I trust you to only add real scores ;)

Have a great day – Marc

PS: Being fast on desktop is a different skill than being fast on mobile.

[1]: https://github.com/remarcable/ClickTheNumber

Show HN: TinyUX – Grid based low-fi wireframing on your mobile phone
text:
You tap icons to create a wireframe, or do some visual brainstorming. Then export the image to share on Slack, Gitlab, etc.

I wanted to work on neural net that interprets an imported image of a wireframe, to then manipulate it inside an app. Figured it would be best to first build the wireframing app. So I created TinyUX.

It's released as quickly as possible this influenced some choices:

- While created in React Native, it's Android only. - It's paid only (~$5). While freemium might make more sense, this was quicker to release, since in-app-purchases in RN is not trivial. First app I created that's not free, so that's an experiment too. - There are no online features, all is stored on the device.

Looking to validate with UX designers, but all feedback is welcome.
